<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-258-796  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 258 796.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 24 1989 n535 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Olympus climbing. (Europe's Olympus 1 communications satellite)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woolnough, Roger.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The European Space Agency (ESA) will launch the Olympus 1, firstin a new program of powerful communications satellites, on anAriane rocket from French Guiana in Jun 1989.andP;  The satellite wasbuilt by a consortium of European aerospace firms led by BritishAerospace Ltd. Olympus 1 will function as a demonstrationmulti-payload platform, as it will carry four payloadapplications: high-power direct broadcast television,videoconferencing, data transmission and educational services.andO;The satellite will be situated at a 19-degrees West longitudegeostationary orbit.andP;  Two steerable antennas can reach allcountries visible from that position.andP;  Olympus 1 has a projected10-year lifetime.andP;  Eight countries are participating in theproject.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Communications SatellitesEuropean Space AgencySystem DesignEuropeOlympus (Artificial satellite).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>